Description:
Learning outcomes:
			To describe and explain the rationale and concepts of SDIs; 
			To explain the requirements for building a successful SDI;
			To recognise and describe the different components of an SDI; 
			To interpret and explain the content of basic XML documents and UML diagrams; 
			Explain the role of metadata in data sharing and data exchange;
			To explain how geoportals are a user interface to SDIs and their specific functions; 
			To design and set-up a simple WMS by making use of a sample dataset and simple portrayal rules; 
			To search and find specific datasets

Learning outcomes: 
			Explain the relevant technological issues around development and implementation of Spatial Data Infrastructures (SDI);
			Identify and discuss the different components of an SDI;
			Develop a strategy to improve the performance of an SDI initiative; 
			Use the models of ‚ÄòSDI generations‚Äô and ‚ÄòSDI components‚Äô to describe the main elements of an existing SDI initiative;			
			Apply the essential elements of business process management to SDI processes; 
			Explain the evolution towards open data policies;
			Design an effective governance structure for a national SDI;
			Describe political, economic, administrative, and other social forces in agencies, organizations, and citizens that inhibit or promote sharing of geospatial and other data;
			Identify barriers for data sharing in your own organisation;
			Explain the link between SDI and other (open) data policies;
			Discuss the governance structure in place of a particular country;
			Explain what SDI governance is and why it is important in the development and implementation of SDIs;
			List and execute the main tasks to be executed in SDI implementation;
			Apply different models of tasks allocation to real SDIs;
			Explain the different instruments for SDI governance;
			Provide examples of existing SDI governance instruments;
			Identify the benefits of an SDI for your organisation;
			Explain the importance of work processes in the context of SDI;
			Prepare a model of an SDI work process; 
			Compare different frameworks for assessing Spatial Data Infrastructures; 
			Design an SDI assessment framework and methodology for assessing and evaluating an SDI; 
			Explain the main objectives of an SDI;
			Explain the results of an SDI assessment

Learning outcomes: Understand Physical Principles which are the basis of Remote Sensing; Understand basis of EM energy and its propagation through the space; Illustrate basic modern physics theory understanding their implications on the development of advanced sensors for EO;
					       Illustrate basic radiation-matter interactions and related concepts of spectral reflectance, absorbance and transmittance as specific properties of the matter; Explain the concept of composition of spectral signatures and apply the 'linear mixing' models in some simple case; Illustrate the concept of spectral signatures of the matter;
					       Illustrate the spectral response curves for basic environmental features (e.g., vegetation, concrete, bare soil);Illustrate basic features of spectral signatures of vegetation, water and bare soil; Illustrate e.m. radiation intercations with/within clouds; 
					       Illustrate main spectral signatures of clouds and apply them in paractical cloud-detection exercise; Explain an application example where the spectral indices are used for vegetation, water or snow monitoring; Examine how the vegetation indices relates to the vegetation dynamics and health;
					       Examine how the water-related spectral indices relates to changes in the vegetation and soil water content; Explain how the NDVI relates to vegetation activity/health; Explain sensitivity of NDVI to the chlorophyll content of vegetation;
					       Knowledge of the basic (selective) mechanism of the absorption/emission of electromagnetic radiation by atoms; Demonstrate the relationships among measured multi-spectral radiation and specific chemical (e.g. composition) and physical (e.g. temperature, pressure, etc.) properties of the observed matter; Explain what microwave remote sensing is; 
					       Explain differences between optical and radar remote sensing; Explain how radar images are used for specific applications; Discuss the main types of remote sensing sensors and platforms;
					       Discuss the main types of remote sensing data; Distinguish and explain the different types of properties of digital imagery; Explain and discuss what the spectral resolution is;
					       Explain and discuss what the spatial resolution is; Explain and discuss what the radiometric resolution is; Explain and discuss what the temporal resolution is;
					       Compare common sensors by spatial resolution, spectral sensitivity, ground coverage, and temporal resolution [e.g., AVHRR, MODIS (intermediate resolution ~500 m, high temporal) Landsat, commercial high resolution (Ikonos and Quickbird); Demonstrate basic knowledge of the interaction between the solar radiation and atmospheric constituents; Discuss types and classes of remote sensing sensors;
					       Select the type of remote sensing sensor appropriate for your application; Explain and discuss types of sensing mechanisms; Discuss advantages and disadvantages of passive and active sensors;
					       Understand sun, sun angle, and sensor parameters that influence top of atmosphere (TOA) reflectance; Understand atmospheric parameters that influence bottom of atmosphere (BOA) reflectance; Discuss the basic principles of solar radiation;
					       Demonstrate basic knowledge of the atmospheric absorption and scattering mechanisms; Illustrate the interaction of e.m. radiation in the thermal infrared with the atmosphere understanding specifc characteristics of radiative transfer in this specific spectral region;
